\pard\plain\ltrpar\qj\fi566\s28\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\s28\f0\fs24\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch 2. Why do I get an OutOfMemory exception and how can I avoid it?}{\s28\f0\fs24\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\qj\fi566\s28\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\s28\f0\fs24\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch You get an OutOfMemory exception because the maximum heap size for the program was reached.}{\s28\f0\fs24\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\qj\fi566\s28\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\s28\f0\fs24\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch Because of the high memory requirements of the langgen tool it's sometimes difficult to avoid the exception. You can try by increasing the maximum memory size used by langgen. You increase the size to 1024MB with this command:}{\s28\f0\fs24\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\fi566\s28\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\s28\f0\fs20\i\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch java -Xms1024m -Xmx1024m -jar LangGenerator myGrammarFile}{\s28\f0\fs20\i\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\fi566\s28\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\s28\f0\fs24\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch The number 1024 represents the wanted size.}{\s28\f0\fs24\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\fi566\s28\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\s28\f0\fs24\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch Because the langgen tool doesn't check for loops in the grammar file it can get caught in such a loop thus filling up the memory.}{\s28\f0\fs24\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}
\pard\plain\ltrpar\ql\fi566\s28\sl240\slmult1\itap0{\s28\f0\fs24\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\abinodiroverride\ltrch Another reason is the complexity of the grammar. The bigger the complexity the bigger the ocupied memory will be. So please fragment and simplify the grammar as much as possible.}{\s28\f0\fs24\lang1033{\*\listtag0}\par}}